choices.text:
for me to go as pedestrian through the hutments where all the people live. As you walk through the huts you are scrutinized so vigorously like not human so I am going there to buy rice and pulses [staples of Indian cooking]. I go past the usual snack vendors, etc. that are usually huddled in Indian buses or trucks turning out chakkali from the huge electric whisk and street vendor style tea from tea leaf and hot water and usually a greasy possibly day old deep fried string or spiced bread to go with it.

A chariot and trailer crossed my path at one point and I was left in the midst of high air pressure and humanity blocking all the air from breathing and the sitting in the sun just exhausted me completely but I had to get home to rest. I used a bicycle for the last stretch and it took almost 100% of my energy in the sun and humidity with the emanation prints ahead of me at every street junction.

The tops of the huts are like mushroom tops all sprawled out and just my height about 4-5' tall. I passed through silently like these huts have never had a rich person go by. . They have food scraps in front of them and "clean" water is not an issue as there are dozens of open drains filled with them mere 20 feet away. There are animals strange and frisky but kept off balanced by the ubiquitous chai provides a handicap; the human feces in the nearby open
